summary:
State aid — agricultural, forestry, fishery and aquaculture sectors
State aid — agricultural, forestry, fishery and aquaculture sectors
SUMMARY OF:
Regulation (EU) No 717/2014 on the application of Articles 107 and 108 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU) to de minimis aid in the fishery and aquaculture sector
Regulation (EU) No 702/2014 declaring certain categories of aid in the agricultural and forestry sectors and in rural areas compatible with the internal market in application of Articles 107 and 108 TFEU
Regulation (EU) No 1388/2014 declaring certain categories of aid to undertakings active in the production, processing and marketing of fishery and aquaculture products compatible with the internal market in application of Articles 107 and 108 TFEU
Regulation (EU) No 1408/2013 on the application of Articles 107 and 108 of TFEU to de minimis aid in the agriculture sector
Guidelines for the examination of State aid to the fishery and aquaculture sector
EU Guidelines for State aid in the agricultural and forestry sectors and in rural areas 2014 to 2020
WHAT IS THE AIM OF THE REGULATIONS AND GUIDELINES?

The legislation aims to make State aid in the agriculture and fishery sectors compatible with the internal market ‘level playing field’ in the way Article 107 and Article 108 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU) are applied:
Regulation (EU) No 717/2014 sets out rules for de minimis* aid in the fishery and aquaculture sector;
Regulation (EU) No 702/2014, known as the Agriculture Block Exemption Regulation (ABER), sets out a sector-specific block exemption for financial aid granted to small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) in the agricultural and forestry sectors and in rural areas;
Regulation (EU) No 1388/2014, known as the fisheries sector Block Exemption Regulation (FIBER), sets out block exemption for financial aid granted to SMEs producing, processing or marketing fishery and aquaculture products;
Regulation (EU) No 1408/2013 sets out rules for de minimis aid in the agricultural sector;
the guidelines lay down the conditions under which State aid is compatible with the internal market in the agricultural, forestry, fishery and aquaculture sectors.
KEY POINTS
Regulation (EU) No 702/2014: Agriculture and forestry
State funding meeting the criteria set out in Article 107(1) of the TFEU constitutes State aid and must be notified to the European Commission. The Council can determine categories of aid that are exempted from this notification requirement.
Aid must be compatible with the internal market under Article 107(2) or (3) and is exempted from the notification requirement of Article 108(3), provided that the aid fulfils all the conditions in this regulation and specific conditions for the relevant category of aid. The regulation is closely related to the common agriculture policy (CAP) and outlines categories of aid compatible with the internal market in the agriculture and forestry sectors.
Aid must be:
transparent;
published, if it exceeds publication thresholds;
have an incentive effect, i.e. aid should change the behaviour of an undertaking in such a way that it engages in additional activity contributing to the development of the sector.
Categories of aid for SMEs in primary agricultural production, processing and marketing
investments in tangible or intangible assets on holdings linked to primary agricultural production (limited to €500,000 per undertaking per project);
agricultural land consolidation;
investments concerning the relocation of farm buildings (limited to €500,000 per project);
investments in connection with processing and marketing agricultural products (limited to €7.5 million per undertaking per investment project;
start-up aid for young farmers and the development of small farms;
start-up aid for producer groups and organisations in the agricultural sector;
participation of producers of agricultural products in quality schemes;
knowledge transfer and information;
advisory services;
farm replacement services;
agricultural product promotion;
compensating for damage caused by adverse climatic events considered to be natural disasters;
prevention, control and eradication of animal diseases and plant pests and to make good any damage caused;
livestock sector and fallen stock;
payment of insurance premiums.
Categories of aid for research and development in the agricultural and forestry sectors
afforestation and the creation of woodland (limited to €7.5 million per establishment project);
agroforestry systems (limited to €7.5 million per agroforestry system establishment project);
prevention and restoration of damage to forests from forest fire, natural disasters, adverse climatic events, plant pests and catastrophic events;
investments improving forest ecosystem resilience and environmental value (limited to €7.5 million per investment project);
disadvantages related to Natura 2000 forest areas;
forest-environmental and climate services and forest conservation;
knowledge transfer and information in the forestry sector;
advisory services in the forestry sector;
investments in infrastructure related to the development, modernisation or adaptation of the forestry sector (limited to €7.5 million per investment project);
investments in forestry technologies and in processing, mobilising and marketing forestry products (limited to €7.5 million per investment project);
conservation of genetic resources in forestry;
forestry land consolidation.
Categories of aid for SMEs in rural areas co-financed by the European Agricultural Fund for Rural Development or additional to such co-financed measures
aid for investments concerning the processing of agricultural products into non-agricultural products or the production of cotton (limited to €7.5 million per investment project);
business start-up aid for non-agricultural activities in rural areas;
aid for advisory services for SMEs in rural areas;
aid for knowledge transfer and information actions in favour of SMEs in rural areas;
aid for new participation of active farmers in quality schemes for cotton and foodstuffs;
aid for information and promotion activities concerning cotton and foodstuffs covered by a quality scheme.
Other categories of agriculture sector aid
investments in conserving cultural and natural heritage located on agricultural holdings (limited to €500,000 per undertaking per investment project, and limited to €10,000 per year for capital works);
repairing damage caused by natural disasters in the agricultural sector;
research and development in the agricultural and forestry sectors (limited to €7.5 million per project).
Regulation (EU) No 1388/2014: Fisheries and aquaculture
State funding meeting the criteria set out in Article 107(1) of the TFEU constitutes State aid and must be notified to the Commission. The Council can determine categories of aid that are exempted from this notification requirement.
The regulation outlines categories of eligible aid compatible with the internal market for fisheries and aquaculture. In each case the aid must fulfil the conditions of the relevant article in Regulation (EU) No 508/2014 (see summary) and the value must not be greater than the amount set by its Article 95 on the intensity of public aid, and subsequent implementing acts (no more than 50% of total costs, with some exemptions).
aid is granted only if it complies with EU laws, particularly the common fisheries policy (CFP);
aid is granted only for projects costing €2 million or less, and with no more than €1 million per beneficiary per year;
aid must have an incentive effect;
written applications must be submitted before work on the project or activity starts.
Categories of aid for sustainable development in fisheries and aquaculture
innovation;
advisory services;
partnership between scientists and fishermen;
promoting human capital, job creation and social dialogue;
facilitating diversification and new forms of income;
start-up support for young fishermen;
improving health and safety;
mutual funds for adverse climatic events and environmental incidents;
support systems for allocating fishing opportunities;
supporting conservation measures and regional cooperation;
limiting the impact of fishing on the marine environment and adapting fishing to protect species;
innovation linked to conserving marine biological resources;
protecting and restoring marine biodiversity and ecosystems and compensation for sustainable fishing;
improving energy efficiency and mitigating the effects of climate change;
added value, product quality and using unwanted catches;
fishing ports, landing sites, auction halls and shelters;
inland fishing and inland aquatic fauna and flora.
Categories of aid for sustainable aquaculture development
innovation in aquaculture;
productive investments in aquaculture;
management, relief and advisory services for aquaculture farms;
promoting human capital and networking in aquaculture;
increasing aquaculture site potential;
encouraging new aquaculture farmers practising sustainable aquaculture;
conversion to eco-management and audit schemes and organic aquaculture;
aquaculture providing environmental services;
public health measures;
animal health and welfare measures;
aquaculture stock insurance.
Marketing, processing, and other categories of aid in fisheries and aquaculture
marketing;
processing of fishery and aquaculture products;
data collection;
making good damage caused by natural disasters;
tax exemptions or reductions.
Regulation (EU) No 717/2014: De minimis aid in the fisheries and aquaculture sectors
De minimis aid is State aid deemed not to meet all the criteria in Article 107(1) TFEU.
EU Member States have to respect a national limit, set out in the regulation’s annex, when granting aid to undertakings active in the fishery and aquaculture sector, and put in place control measures to check that the rules have been complied with.
De minimis aid, in particular:
has to be transparently managed;
may not be used to buy fishing vessels or engines, to increase fishing capacity or the ability to find fish, or any other ineligible operations;
may not be above the ceiling of €30,000 for any undertaking in a 3-year period, or 2.5% of the annual catching, processing and aquaculture turnover per Member State.
Regulation (EU) No 1408/2013: De minimis aid in the agricultural sector
De minimis aid is State aid deemed not to meet all the criteria in Article 107(1) TFEU.
Member States have to respect a national limit set out in the regulation’s annex when granting aid to undertakings active in primary agricultural production, and put in place control measures to check that the rules have been complied with.
De minimis aid, in particular:
has to be transparently managed;
may not be based on the price or amounts put on the market, export-related or dependent on the use of domestic products;
may not be above the ceiling of €20,000 for any undertaking in a 3-year period, or national cap of 1% of the annual agricultural output.
However, Member States may increase the aid amount per single undertaking to €25,000 and the national limit to 1.5% of the annual output, on condition that a Member State must not spend more than 50% of its total national aid budget on one single product sector.
Guidelines for State aid in the agricultural and forestry sectors and in rural areas
It sets out the conditions and criteria under which aid for the agricultural and forestry sectors and for rural areas will be considered to be compatible with the internal market. These conditions and criteria include common assessment principles and specific conditions and criteria for various categories of aid.
Guidelines for the examination of State aid to the fishery and aquaculture sector
It sets out the conditions and criteria under which aid for the fishery and aquaculture sector will be considered to be compatible with the internal market. These conditions and criteria include common assessment principles and specific conditions and criteria for various categories of aid.
FROM WHEN DO THE REGULATIONS AND GUIDELINES APPLY?

Regulations (EU) No 717/2014 and (EU) No 702/2014 entered into force on 1 July 2014 and initially applied until 31 December 2020.
Regulation (EU) No 1388/2014 entered into force on 1 January 2015 and initially applied until 31 December 2020.
Regulation (EU) 2020/2008 extends their validity until 31 December 2022.
Regulation (EU) No 1408/2013 entered into force on 1 July 2014 and initially applied until 31 December 2020.
Regulation (EU) 2019/316 extends its validity until 31 December 2027.
Fishery and aquaculture guidelines have applied since 1 July 2015.
EU agriculture guidelines have applied since 1 July 2014. They initially applied until 31 December 2020 and the notice amending it extended their validity until 31 December 2022.
BACKGROUND

See also:
Competition: Agriculture, food and fisheries — Overview (European Commission).
KEY TERMS

De minimis aid: aid which does not meet all the criteria in Article 107(1) of the TFEU, and is exempt from the notification requirement in Article 108(3), which fulfils the conditions set out in the regulation and do not exceed €30,000 for each undertaking over any 3-year period.
